column168: On 05/6/2013 at approximately 0030 a leaking shipment was reported by sort personnel at DHL Express 236 Wendell H Ford Blvd, Erlanger KY, 41018.   Upon arrival there was found, 1 fiberboard box that appeared wet on the outside.  Inside the fiberboard box was found a glass bottle containing 2 liters of product.  The plastic cap on the glass bottle was broken causing the loss of approximately 4 ounces of product.  Tracking indicates initial transportation by air.

Bags have been damaged from rubbing against side of trailer. Other freight appear to have struck bags releasing towards nose of trailer. One of the pallets was place against a brace bars. The weight of the pallet during transit caused bags to tear against brace bar. Nothing was placed in between the pallet and bar to protect from damage. While contractor was repalletizing bags of freight, it appears all 99 bags are damaged. The bags are poorly sealed and releasing from seams. Contractor will place each bag in a plastic bag for containment and repalletize.
column169: Implement better blocking and bracing practices to prevent future occurrences.

column168: Driver of a cargo tank hauling liquid fuels Gasoline swerved to miss a deer and caught a tire in the soft shoulder which then pulled the Tractor trailer off the road way and the result was a 3/4 rollover off the steep embankment. The rollover caused the # 1 compartment vent to fail and a slow release of approximately 1200 gals of fuel over an 8 hour period until the fuel could be safely recovered. Then the recovery of the tractor trailer began upon completion of that recovery, J C Hunt has acquired the remedial services of Envirotech for the cleanup process. Envirotech was on the scene of the accident and performed a temporary containment of the spill until proper permits are obtained. The complete cleanup is still in process with Envirotech. Contact information is Felipe Aragon cell # 505-947-2332
column169: J C Hunt has in place a monthly Safety training program. We will continue this program with an increased emphasis on Defensive driving and road hazard awareness to the specific areas we perform transportation services. We are in the process of equipping all of our trucks with heavy duty bumpers for animal prevention to help prevent the need for unnecessary and unsafe maneuvers. We will retrain the driver involved in the accident and reevaluate his return to duty status upon completion of a road test.

column168: A van trailer containing a shipment of hazardous waste was to be unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation on another trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  Upon opening the doors, a strong odor was noticed.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A tote with a defective valve was found to have leaked approximately a quart of liquid onto the trailer floor.  No material leaked onto the ground.  The contents of the defective tote were transferred into another tote and the shipment was loaded onto the other trailer without further incident.  The trailer floor was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound.  The State of Ohio EPA was notified and assigned incident number 1305-18-0991.
column169: The tote was not leaking at the time of pickup.  The valve was replaced on the tote and it was placed back into service.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery, a strong odor was detected inside the trailer and several wet cartons were discovered.  The trailer was isolated and SWS Environmental was dispatched to inspect the trailer and perform the necessary cleanup.  SWS Environmental inspected the trailer and discovered two (2) damaged cartons, each containing four (4) one-gallon plastic jugs.  Two jugs inside one of the cartons were damaged.  Apparently the damage was the result of a puncture by a forklift.  An estimated two gallons were released and impacted adjacent freight.  SWS Environmental removed all of the freight and performed the necessary cleanup of the impacted freight.  The freight and waste was left on the trailer pending further instructions.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However Roadrunner Transportation Services, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Shipment received on non-hazardous manifest WMNH00018024 on 5/2/13. Manifest included one line item: 115 CF of Universal Waste Lamps, DOT non-regulated. Inspection of the shipment found 2 DFs of assorted batteries including dry nickel-cadmium, lead acid and lithium batteries. Batteries were sorted and segregated upon receipt. While the batteries may be shipped as Universal Waste on a non-hazardous manifest, they should have been packaged separately and identified as Universal Waste batteries and DOT regulated hazardous materials on the shipping paper: UN3090, Lithium battery, 9, II UN2794, Batteries, wet, filled with acid, 8, III Batteries, dry, sealed, N.O.S.
column169: The customer was contacted and the discrepancy was explained. Guidance on shipping batteries was provided.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 A.M., UPS EMPLOYEES AT THE SYRACUSE HUB NOTICED A FIRE INVOLVING A PACKAGE MARKED AS CONSUMER COMMODITY, ORM-D. QUICK ACTION BY AN EMPLOYEE WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER SUPPRESSED THE FIRE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO DAMAGE TO OTHER PACKAGES, PACKAGE SORTING EQUIPMENT, OR THE FACILITY. SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION SHOWED THE PACKAGE TO BE A CASE OF SPRAY PAINT. ONE OF THE AEROSOL CANS APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED JUST ABOVE THE BOTTOM RIM. CONVEYOR BELTS, SUCH AS THE ONE ON WHICH THE SUBJECT PACKAGE WAS TRAVELING, ARE KNOWN TO GENERATE STATIC ELECTRICITY, WHICH LIKELY IGNITED THE FLAMMABLE CONTENTS RELEASED FROM THE PUNCTURED CAN.
column169: UPS HAS PETITIONED FOR PACKAGING IMPROVEMENTS APPLICABLE TO AEROSOLS SUCH AS DIVIDERS OR OTHER CUSHIONING THAT WOULD PREVENT CAN-TO-CONTACT THAT CAUSES PUNCTURES SUCH AS EXHIBITED HERE.

column168: Safety contacted ERTS in regards to an ammonia solution, Caustic alkali liquids, n.o.s. (ammonia complex solution), release located at 234 Donovan Road in Kansas City, Kansas. It was reported that due to the strong odor within the trailer, the trailer had been secured in the yard. It was initially estimated that approximately 1-2 gallons of material was released to the exterior of the trailer. Per MSDS 29.4% ammonia solution.    Contractor located the leaking container, contractor reported that the leaking drum was located at the nose of the trailer. Contractor estimated that approximately 3-4 gallons of material was released from the drum. Contractor reported that the bung was completely removed from the drum and was sitting to the side of the drum resulting in the release. Contractor resecured the bung of the drum and neutralized the released material.

column168: When maneuvering into position at the consignee, the Quality Carriers driver noticed product dripping from the top of CTMV.  The Quality Carriers driver inspected the CTMV and found that the front clean-out cap was missing.  It was secure during his pre-trip inspection earlier that morning.  Approximately 50 gallons of product spilled onto the side of the CTMV and onto the cement parking area.  The release occurred only when our driver was maneuvering the CTMV    Quality Carriers sent a local emergency response contractor to assist remediation.  Consignee personnel cleaned up the product from the cement, and the contractor cleaned off the CTMV exterior.  A clean-out cap was installed.  The remaining product was unloaded without further incident.    The Quality Carriers Event Number is 37143.

column168: On May 1, 2013 at approximately 09:46 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Fredericksburg, VA yard discovered NATX 364034, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, ECO Energy Representative Brian Downy at 615-778-2594, local, state and/or federal agencies as applicable were notified. CHEMTREC Report  2013-05-01-00081. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the 3 inch liquid line valve less than tool tight. Contractor personnel tightened the valve tool tight and the leak was secured.  The car was held awaiting ECO Energy to apply for an OTMA to move the car to be offloaded and then sent to a shop for a leakproof test to be performed.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident does not require a 7.1    Cause Code: 282  NARRI: 5(5+3+0)X(2+0)=80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: This was a unserviceable Slide property of Alaska Arilines that our vendor Amsafe was returning to SEA.  This was a repair order that needs to be shipped  to their other facility. Note: I previously had made up an incident report yesterday 5/20/13 under Tracking # 561791 but could not be found by transportation depart...   I am making another report.

DID NIGHTLY DMP AREA CHECK, FOUND UNMARKED CARBOARD LEAKING PACKAGE IN DMP AREA, OPENED FOR INSPECTION, FOUND INNER CARDBOARD PACKAGING, OPENED INNER PACKAGE, FOUND 4 - 1 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINERS OF PRODUCT, PLACED CONTAINERS IN SPILL TUB, AFTER REMOVING DAMAGED PLASTIC CONTAINERS WAS ABLE TO INSPECT INNER CARDBOARD PACKAGE, FOUND UN SPEC MARKINGS ON TOP OF INNER CARBOARD BOX, LIFTED INNER BOX OUT OF OUTER BOX AND SAW  CLASS 6 DIAMOND HAZMAT LABEL ON 1 SIDE OF INNER PACKAGING. CHECKED PROHIBITED HAZMAT POSTER AND FOUND CLASS 6 LABEL NOT ALLOWED IN UPS SYSTEM, FOLLOWING DECISION TREE CONTACTED CHAIN OF COMMAND AND P.E., OUTSIDE RESPONDER NOTIFIED TO HANDLE THIS INCIDENT - NO SHIPPING PAPERS ON INNER HAZMAT MARKED PACKAGE

column168: THIS SHIPMENT SPILLED DURING THE SORT. AN EMPLOYEE MARVIN HEGLER, #380301 WHO WAS WEARING GLOVES, DID GET IT ON HIS HANDS AND IT BURNED. HE WASHED OFF THEM LATER OPTED TO SEE A DOCTOR. HE RECEIVED FIRST AID AT HAYWORTH, THEN WENT TO US HEALTH WORKS TO SEE THE DOCTOR. HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED. THE PACKAGE, WHICH HAD NOT BEEN OFFERED BY THE SHIPPER WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, LABELING, NOR WITH A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION, IS BELIVED TO BE UNDECLARED DG. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER. SECTION 14 CLEARLY STATES IT AS UN 3149, HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURE, STABLIZED, 5.1 (8), II. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.
column169: THIS SHIPPER WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED ON THE FEDEX EMBARGO LIST FOR ALL BOX FREIGHT. THEY MUST SHOW PROOF OF TRAINING AND AN ACTION PLAN TO BE TAKEN OFF THE EMBARGO.

Incident involved spillage of 30 gallons of diethanolamine (DEA) during top/splash loading of DEA into a liquid trailer from the loading spout. DEA has a freezing point of 86 degrees F.    Package did not fail.    The loading spout was short and secured to the trailers dome collar with a clamp.  Residual DEA from prior loading activities is believed to have been frozen within the loading hose, in low spots.  This resulted in fluctuations in pressure during this loading activity.  These fluctuations resulted in the clamp working free and a sudden increase in pressure forced the spout up onto the top of the trailer.
column169: 1. The exisiting load spout inserts into the trailer dome 12”, and uses a single wing clamp to stabilize and secure the spout. There is no deflector attached to the end of the load spout to redirect the upward pressure from loading, in order to keep the spout from attempting to rise out of tank during loading.   Design - Load spout should at a minimum insert into tank 30” and have a deflector installed, and use a lock down bar attachment to stabilize load spout.  These enhancements are being reviewed by operations for application.    2. Current loading design uses hoses. This design uses a sling to support hoses in the overhead. The DEA hose essentially has two low spots where product can settle and freeze (freezing point is 86 degrees F). The hose is not heat traced nor insulated to prevent freezing.  Design - operations is investigating options for heat tracing, insulating the hoses.      3. It has been a standard practice at the Chester Terminal to remove frozen product at the end of the hose by “digging it out” and then installing the load spout.  The loading process would then begin.   Operational Training - Employees have been training to recognize that when an abnormal condition is identified they must “STOP” and notify Supervision.

On 05/14/2013, a truck driver noticed product dripping from container ZIMU 101573 (L/ p-Chlorobenzotriflouride, UN2234) while picking up the load at CN Gateway Intermodal Terminal, Harvey, IL. All appropriate departments notified. CNs response team responded noting product dripping from the left side of the container, near the doorway area. Doorway seal intact. The container doors were opened and a 55 gallon metal drum located on the top row, L/side was found leaking. Leak was noted coming from the base of the drum where a protruding nail head to the pallets' 3"x3" support damaged the drum.  The damaged drum was placed in an over pack drum for securement. The rest of load was transferred and properly secured into another container. Containers were released for movement.

According to the information obtatined, the following occurred.  While traveling, Jensen Transport vehicle was clipped by a train, which caused truck to rollover onto its side and release product.  The capacity of the tanker is 40,000 pounds.  The Local Fire Department responded to apply water to the overturned tanker and reduce vapor cloud emitting from the cargo tank.  Immediate area was evacuated as a precautionary measure, due to the heavy vapors.  Swift County Emergency Management Agency and Chemical Assessment Team responded to assess the site, along with the Minnesota Department of Agriculture.  West Central Environmental Consultants of Morris, Minnesota was dispatched to assist in cleanup.  Burlington Northern Sante Fe Railyard contracted Specialized Response Solutions (SRS) to transfer product from the damaged tanker, into a rescue tanker provided by Jensen Transport.   Approximately 20,000 pounds of anhydrous ammonia were recovered into the rescue tanker.  The Local Fire Department continued to spray water onto the damaged tank until no further vapors were released.  West Central Environmental Consultants proceeded to recover the contaminated waters from the site.  Center for Toxicology and Environmental Health were on site to monitor the air and ensure safe levels within immediate area.  WCEC pulled soil samples from the adjacent soils in the area, per Minnesota DOT, and site will be monitored to ensure all levels of contamination have been recovered.
column169: Jensen Transport will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Univar driver Jose Alberto Estrada loaded a load of  93% Sulfuric Acid at Rhodia in Long Beach, Ca. Jose proceeded to take a sample of the product after the loading was completed.  A few drops of product fell in the spill dam on top of the trailer while filling the sample bottle.  He stepped away from washing the the dome area to secure and place the sample bottle away for the lab on his equipment.  He continued to process paperwork and started to drive towards the truck scale, completely forgeting to tighten the dome lid bolts.  He weighed the trailer at the scale and did not notice that some product had spilled from the domelid area on the scale at 4:03 PM.  Once he reached the curb on S. Wilminton Avenue out of Rhodia driveway, Rhodia employees noticed that the trailer#171 had leaked some product on the scale and scrambled to check if it was 93% Sulfuric or water.    Meanwhile, Jose proceeded out of the Rhodia facility driving towards Del Amo intersection on Wilmington Avenue unaware the spill had occurred at Rhodia Driveway & scale area.  When Jose reached the intersection of Del Amo and Wilmington, product also spilled at the intersection from the domelid area.  This spill was concentrated only on the right hand lane close to the property of Rhodia. Jose continued to drive toward the railroad track after crossing the intersection of Del Amo & Wilmington where he made the mandatory stop at the railroad crossing.  At that point, he looked in the side view mirror to see if he could move forward, & he noticed a puddle of liquid at the intersection leading upto his trailer where he was.  He proceeded to stop the trailer away from the railway crossing and started to make calls & place the safety cones to block the street of vehicles from getting 93% Sulfuric acid on their equipment.  Due to the rush hour traffic, he proceeded to call 911 to help with assiting the traffic flow, there was also a risk of product entering the storm drain.  Jose continued to place absorbant pads near the storm drain and prevented a majority of the product from entering the storm drain.    Rhodia personnel called our dispatch simultaneously while Jose was calling us to inform of the spill.  Phone calls were made to DOM, ROM and WER Regulatory Manager regarding the incident & all the pertinent agencies were informed soon after.  Incident # with CalEPA is 13-2778 & NRC#104-6476.
column169: Several changes have been recommended by employees and invetigating team to prevent from happening in the future;  • Completed Incident investigation – all action items have been completed, the action items completed are:           1. Place seals on domelids and documented on shipping documents.          2. Audit weekly to see if the drivers are sealing the domelids with seals that match the shipping documents.          3. Drivers to walk the long way around the tractor and trailer to carryout another visual inspection before they leave the yard to go towards public roads.          4. Retrain employees in Univar policy for loading and unloading trailers in lieu of changes above.  • Final warning reprimand letter given to Jose Alberto Garcia – driver involved in the incident & with 3 days with out pay.  He will go through 2 weeks of training before he is back on the job by himself.  • Ops. Training given to Jose Alberto Garcia following the accident    • Loading/off-loading checklist – we are requiring all our drivers, bulk or mini-bulk drivers to fill in going forward which includes checking all valves and opening that can potentially leak over the road.    • A box of seals have been ordered for Rhodia Dominguez facility, these seals will be used by contract transporters and Univar drivers alike for securing the domelids and documenting to make sure this does not happen again.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: At approx 6:30 pm on 5-2-13 our driver was negotiating a turn on Hwy 17.   The trailer and truck rolled over on its passenger side.  The vehicle came to rest on its top.    This was reported to our company by a bystander.  He was one of the first on scene but did not witness the accident.    We called the NM State patrol they confirmed it was an Alta Truck and were already responding.  We immediately called CES and sent personnel to the scene.  The scene was blocked two miles from the site.    CES Arrived approximately 02:30.  They allowed us to dispatch a truck around 7am on 5-3-13. Representatives were allowed on scene around 8:30 am to pump out any remaining material from the trailer.  By then there were Sorbent pads under the trailer and truck and snakes were placed down the ditch for 300 to 500 ft.    Hazmat was steadily release from a tear towards the front of the trailer approximately 12 inches in length for approximately 14 hours.
column169: We Acknowledge this question; however we will have a better plan of action to reort following our Federal D.O.T. audit scheduled for June, 10, 2013.    Note on Part IV 32. Damages are well over 500.00. I do not have these numbers yet, as it is too soon to get this information from the Insurance Company.    Note on Part II 16. The electronic form doesn't let us put more than one product, so I have put the most dangerous one.  There was also 996 gallons of NA1993,Diesel,3,III that spilled in this incident.

column168: A Texas DOT Rail Safety Investigator inspecting rail cars that recently arrived on a BNSF inbound train in the railyard reported tank car UTLX 208559 with evidence of commodity spillage around its manway nozzle and top shell areas.  All manway bolts, valves and other closures were reported secure. A non-sealing manway gasket was suspected as the pathway of the observed spillage. BNSF mechanical responders replaced the manway nozzle gasket applied on UTLX 208559 with a new manway gasket and all the manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened on 5/07/2013. Intact shipper seal numbered 0164114 at the manway closure was replaced by seal numbered 172256.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

BNSF mechanical responders replaced the deteriorated hard manway lid gasket applied on UTLX 211238 with a new manway gasket and all the manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened on 5/06/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: NATX 81184 was found by Chip Heard, MHM for UPRR, during a routine tank car inspection to be releasing vapor from the manway.  The manway bolts were checked and tool tight.  The manway cover was opened and it was determined that the gasket was severely deteriorated and held in place with a silicone type substance.  The silicone substance was removed from the manway cover and a temporary gasket installed.  The manway was closed and properly secured and the car released back into transportation.
column169: Talked with both the shipper and consignee on checking gaskets as well as setting up a schedule for changing manway gaskets.  Also discussed general inspection practices before releasing the car for transportation.

column25: CHS Inc. by Valero Marketing + Supply Company
column168: Tank car UTLX 204319 in the railyard was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area with spillage on its side shell. A mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 204319 finding the threaded liquid valve leaking commodity at its threaded connection. The liquid valve was in the closed position, but 1/4 turn loose on its threaded connection with ineffective thread sealant applied. The responder reduced the internal pressure within UTLX 204319 and removed the liquid valve. The threaded connection was cleaned and new thread sealant applied onto the threads. The liquid valve was then re-installed and properly tool tightened. Afterwards, no additional commodity release was observed from the liquid valve's threaded fitting.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On May 17, 2013, at 1624 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Russell Yard, Russell, Kentucky noticed an odor near GATX 3179, a loaded tank car of UN1824, Sodium Hydroxide Solution. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Marathon Petroleum, was notified via direct phone call to Roger Spring 606-922-7208. Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Russell Yard. Quick Response found the reclosing external pressure relief device (PRD) faulty and in an open position thus allowing the release of product and vapors. The PRD was wrapped with plastic to contain all odors until a permanent repair could be made. The residual material on the tank car was neutralized. The shipper representative, Roger Spring, was notified of the situation found and was to make arrangements to have a qualified repair facility replace the PRD. Marathon Petroleum will secure an OTMA 3 after replacement of the PRD and then have the tank car requalified at their facility.     This incident did require a special move.    A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report is required for this incident.    NARRI: 2x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 40  Cause code: 421

DSR was unloading trailer 313-9339 on 5-3-2013 around 8am and heard a leaking air sound. DSR notified me(David Dubey) I walked into the trailer and determined it was comming from one of the big tanks of liquid nitrogen. I called the emergency contact on the b.o.l. and spoke with Dave Stout(Air Products) 1-610-481-2518. at that point Dave told me it was probably a relief valve, he said they were meant to do that. Dave said when the valve stopped leaking then we could move the tanks. I called Larry Fennell let him know what was going on. I kept checking the trailer for the leak and it was still leaking. about two hours after the original discovery of the leak I called Dave Stout again. He said it should stop after a little while. So, Dan Sulich and I have been in contact everyday with Air Products and Chemicals letting them know this is still leaking. They said the same thing stay out of the trailer and after it's done leaking then we can deliver the rest of the freight. I called Larry Fennell on 5/9/2013 and Larry told me to contact the customer and tell them they need to take care of this today or we will have to call someone in to do it. I called the emergency contact number 1-610-481-7711 at Air Products and they are currently finding me someone to come take care of their freight.

column168: Load was in transit from Portland OR to East Chicago,IN Driver stopped in Jerome,ID and preformed a safety check on load and noticed liquid on the floor of the trailer, he attempted to locate the origin of the leak but was unable to identify the specific drum. He called into dispatch and reported the incident. Dispatch notified the Univar shipping office. Univar declined to call out a emergency responder and requested that Savannah contact someone to handle the clean up. Savannah then called the emergency response number on the manifest and was again told to contact a responder for clean up services and refer to Univar report number 116957. Savannah complied with their request and call Specialty Environmental Services (Haz-Mat responder) a team was sent from Bosie,ID to Jerome,ID. The response team needed to several rows of drums to locate the actual leaking drum. A small hole on the bottom of the barrel was found. It was determined to be a packaging failure due to corrosion/aging drum. The drum was then over-packed, trailer cleaned and spill containment material package for shipment to destination with no further incident.

column168: Intermodal container TRHU 236961, destined for export overseas, was reported leaking liquid during deramping from its intermodal rail flatcar at the intermodal facility. TRHU 236961 was immediately taken to the facility's containment area for lading inspection. Contract responders reported finding two 55 gallon steel drums with rolling hoop damage consisting of creases with one inch fractures at the end of these creases. The lading inside TRHU 236961 showed no signs of in transit load shifting, therefore it was likely that the drum damage incurred during drum loading at origin. Both leaking drums were placed into overpack/disposal drums along with another drum that was damaged but not leaking. All three damaged drums were earmarked for off-site disposal. TRHU 236961 was cleaned of any observed spillage and all intact lading was reloaded into TRHU 236961 properly blocked and braced for continued transportation.

column168: Tank car UTLX 23310 in the railyard was reported emanating a strong commodity odor with no liquid release observed. UTLX 23310 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting inspection by contract responders. Initial responders' inspection of UTLX 23310 revealed all valve and fittings were secure. The odor source was thought to be dried residue spillage (from loading) on the tank shell and responders cleaned this spillage using bleach, a bio-degradable cleaner and then wiped. Afterwards, re-inspection of UTLX 23310 by responders due to a faint commodity odor still detectable revealed that the vacuum relief valve (VRV) was the source point of the odor/vapor release. The faulty VRV that would not reseat was removed and a bolted flange plate was applied over the vacated VRV orifice by 1545 hrs. CDT, 5/14/2013, thus eliminating any further vapor/odor releases. UTLX 23310 is awaiting FRA OTMA authority for furtherance in transportation.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On May 22, 2013, the Battelle Receiving and Shipping Warehouse (in-transit storage) received an unmarked box with only the names and addresses.  There were no markings or labels and no shipping paper to identify hazardous materials.  Lacking sufficient information on the intended recipient and with no indication of hazardous materials, the package was opened to search for a packing list.  Buried in packing peanuts was a taped metal tube.  On observing the tube, the staff member reported a "suspicious" item to management.  Subsequent investigations determined the tube contained three 50 g containers of titanium hydride.  Material was repackaged by a qualified shipper for delivery to the final destination.  There were no damage, releases, injuries or costs incurred.

column168: Tank car UCLX 30147 was reported venting in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical responder inspected UCLX 30147 and reported finding a light vapor mist emanating from the rupture disc assembly. The 165 psi frangible disc had burst and the three quick inspect body bolts at the rupture disc holder were finger loose. The responder tightened these three loose bolts. Also, the fill hole cover locking bar's securement nut was not fully tool tight and it was tightened. UCLX 30147 deemed safe to move was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting frangible disc replacement. Shipper representatives replaced the frangible disc in kind and neutralized/decontaminated commodity spillage around the disc housing area by 0850 hrs. CDT, 5/22/2013.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: THE DRIVER WENT TO THE CAB OF HIS TRUCK TRACTOR FOR A FEW MINUTES WILE THE TRANSFER PUMP ON HIS TANKER TRAILER WAS OPERATING (OFF-UNLOADING).  WHEN HE RETURNED, A SPILL HAD OCCURRED.  APPARENTLY, A SPIKE IN PRESSURE IN THE TRANSFER LINE CAUSED THE PRESSURE RELIEF BURST DISK TO OPEN AND DISCHARGE MATERIAL ON TO A CONCRETE PAD.  THE DRIVER SHUT THE TRANSFER PUMP OFF.  DUE TO THE SIZE OF THE SPILL, CALLED HIS DISPATCHER.  THE COMPANY'S SPILL RESPONSE PLAN WAS INITIATED, AND A QUALIFIED SPILL CONTACTOR PROVIDED CLEANUP AND RECOVERY SERVICES.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT INCLUDE:    1. REVIEW DRIVER OFF-LOADING WORK PROCEDURES TO DETERMINE IF AN ENGINEERING OR ADMINISTRATIVE CONTROL MEASURE COULD MITIGATE THE OCCURRENCE OF HIGH PRESSURE SPIKES DURING MATERIAL TRANSFER.    2. REVIEW POTENTIAL ENGINEERING AND ADMINISTRATIVE CONTROLS THAT COULD KEEP THE DRIVER AT THE CONTROLS OF THE TANKER TRAILER TRANSFER PUMP DURING OFF-LOADING.    3. REVIEW OFF-LOADING WORK PROCEDURES AND SPILL RESPONSE FOR THE MINOR AND MAJOR UNLOADING SPILLS WITH DRIVERS OF TANKERS HAULING THE SAME MATERIAL INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT.    4. PROVIDE DRIVERS WITH A WALLET CARD OF THE COMPANY'S USA SPILL FIRM, AND PLACE A DECAL IN EVERY CAB WITH THE SAME INFORMATION APPEARING ON THE WALLET CARD.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, vehicle was involved in an accident, which damaged the cargo tanker, and caused a fire to ignite in vehicle.  Approximately 7,700 gallons of diesel fuel were lost as a result of the accident and subsequent fire.  Local Fire Department and Dauphin County Hazmat responded to assess the site.  Local Fire Department responded to assess the site and extinguish the fire.  The water applied to extinguish the fire, mixed in with the diesel fuel released from the vehicle, and traveled into the storm drain system, which led to Paxtons Creek, eventually entering into the lake at the Wildwood Park Nature Reserve.  Pennsylvania DEP and Dauphin County Hazmat deployed hard boom and absorbent boom to the affected area to assist in containment efforts.   Environmental Products & Services of VT responded to perform the cleanup.  EP&S of VT utilized vacuum trucks to recover diesel fuel and water from Paxtons Creek and the Wildwood Preserve Lake.  Hard containment boom was deployed to contain released fuel and recovery efforts were ongoing throughout the evening to recover gross contamination and minimize impact.  EP&S of VT flushed the storm drain system, and performed air monitoring at the site,  continuing  recovery efforts and site monitoring, until all contamination was recovered.  There were no reported injuries or exposures.

column168: Pilot/Flying J contacted ERTS to dispatch a contractor to cleanup a gasoline release from a punctured tanker as a result of an incident while unloading at the truck stop. The release impacted the parking lot, drains and a retention pond, but did not escape the site. The contractor plugged the punctured hole and the remaining fuel was delivered to the truck stop and put into the UST's on site. The contractor utilized a vacuum truck to recover the fuel from the impacted drains and retention pond and transported that waste off site for disposal. The contractor then applied absorbents to the impacted areas, worked the absorbents in and swept the impacted areas clean. All waste was containerized and left on site for Pilot to coordinate the disposal.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling,  truck was involved in a single-vehicle accident, which caused vehicle to rollover onto its side, damaging freight inside the trailer.  State and local authorities responded to assess the site, to include Winfield Fire Department, Putnam County EMS, Putnam County Sheriff's Department, WV Department of Transportation, Nitro, St. Albans, and Charleston FD personnel, and WV Department of Highways.  Hurricane Wrecker was contacted to recover vehicle and assist in stabilizing trailer during offload.  Haz-Tech Environmental was dispatched to perform the cleanup, and DOW Chemical, shipper of product, was on site to oversee response actions.  Approximately 300 gallons of corrosive liquid, toxic, n.o.s. were releaed from the damaged freight, and approximately 150 gallons of diesel fuel were released from the saddle tanks on the vehicle.  Haz-Tech Environmental offloaded the freight from the damaged trailer, repalletized, and reloaded onto a recovery trailer provided by Hurricane Wrecker.  Nine (9) 55-gallon drums were discovered damaged inside the trailer, which were overpacked and placed onto recovery trailer, along with 71 unbreached drums.  HazTech Environmental used a vacuum truck to recover free liquids from immediate area and nearby storm drain catch basins, and excavated the contaminated soils.  Free product was contained to immediate drains, and did not migrate or threaten waters of the state.  Approximately 800 gallons of liquid waste, 14 tons of contaminated soils and absorbents, and nine (9) overpack drums were generated during initial response.  Absorbent boom was left on site, as a precautionary measure, to prevent residual contamination.  Confirmation samples were pulled and site is being monitored, pending closure.  Disposal was coordinated in accordanced with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.

CN mechanical department employee reported vapors coming from the top of tank car UTLX 130501 (L / HYDROCHLORIC ACID) during a mechanical inspection at the CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, LA.  All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the vapor valve in the open position, 1 of the 4 blind flange bolts attached to the vapor valve missing and the other 3 bolts loose.  The valve was closed,  loose bolts tightened and a new bolt was properly installed. No further release was noted.   The exterior of the railcar was decontaminated and released for movement to the shipper.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: CN transportation department employee reported vapors coming from the top of tank car UTLX 130109 (R / HYDROCHLORIC ACID) during a switching operations near the Old Geismar Depot (Baton Rouge Subdivision MP # 386) Geismar, LA.  All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated in place. CN's response team responded noting vapors coming from the rupture disk housing area.  The rupture disk was checked and appeared to be deteriorated.  A new disk was installed and the leak stopped. Car released to shipper for movement to destination..

column168: Tank car PROX 40434 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and PROX 40434 was isolated awaiting inspection by contract responders. Responders' inspection revealed that the leak source was at the closed liquid valve's valve stem. PROX 40434 deemed safe to move was carefully moved to the facility's containment area (drip pit) for additional inspection and securement. Responders reported the liquid valve's valve stem packing retainer plate was loose with one stud nut missing and the other less than tool tight (finger loose). A replacement stud nut was procured and applied to the bolt stud. Both stud nuts were than properly tool tightened which ended any further commodity release from the liquid valve's valve stem. Spillage on PROX 40436 was wiped and no ground impact from spillage was observed.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Highway 60 near mile post 238 the tractor-trailer unit was involved in a vehicle accident.  As a result of the accident, the tractor and trailer unit rolled-over, resulting in damage to the tractor and a leak from one of the stainless steel tanks on the trailer.  Approximately 30 gallons of diesel fuel and 20 gallons of sulfuric acid were released and impacted the asphalt roadway surface and soil adjacent to the shoulder of the road.  The Arizona Department of Transportation responded to assess the site.  Environmental Response, Inc. was dispatched to complete the cleanup.  The unit was up-righted and the remaining product was removed from the two tanks on the trailer.  Environmental Response, Inc. deployed absorbent material to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  At the time of this report, site excavation is still pending.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Bulk Transportation will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: THE COMPANY VEHICLE COMBINATION CONSISTED OF A 3 AXLE CLASS 8 TRUCK WITH AN LPG CARGO TANK MOUNTED. IT PULLED THE SUBJECT TRAILER WITH AN LPG CARGO TANK INTEGRALLY MOUNTED. THE COMPANY VEHICLE DRIFTED OFF THE ROAD PAVEMENT ONTO A SOFT SHOULDER. IN AN ATTEMPT TO RETURN TO THE PAVEMENT, OUR DRIVER SET IN MOTION A CHAIN OF EVENTS CAUSING THE TRAILER TO ROCK FROM SIDE TO SIDE, OVERTURN, AND SLIDE APPROXIMATELY 300 FEET. DURING THE SLIDE, THE ROAD PAVEMENT ABRADED THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER'S LPG CARGO TANK. NO PACKAGE/TANK FAILURE OCCURRED BUT REPORTING REQUIREMEMTS MET DUE TO INSPECTION AND REPAIR RESULTING FROM INCIDENT. THE TANK SHELL RECEIVED SIGNIFICANT ABRASION DAMAGE FROM SLIDING ON THE HIGHWAY PAVEMENT.
column169: REFRESHER TRAINING FOR ALL DRIVERS ON TANKER ROLLOVER PREVENTION. THIS HAS BEEN ACCOMPLISHED IN A RECENT ROUND OF COMPANY SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: TANK TRAILER HAD EXCESSIVE AMOUNT OF HARDENED ASPHALT OIL IN BOTTOM FROM A PREVIOUS LOAD. LOADED TANKER ACROSS STREET FROM YARD WITH 350 DEGREE ASPHALT OIL TO SOFTEN UP HARD ASPHALT ON BOTTOM. BROUGHT BACK INTO ATI YARD TO OFF-LOAD IN MORNING. EVIDENTLY, MOISTURE HAD GOTTEN INTO TANK FROM RAIN & WASN'T  NOTICEABLE WHEN DRIVER PRE-TRIPPED TANK. WATER IN TANK CAUSED A BOIL-OVER, OVER-PRESSURING TANK & BLOWING OUT DOME LID, GASKET. HOT OIL LEAKED DOWN SIDES OF TRAILER ONTO PARKING LOT. CONTAINED OIL WITH SAND AROUND PERIMETER. CALLED "OMI INC" (OIL MOP) FOR CONTAINMENT, CLEAN-UP, & WASTE DISPOSAL. ASPHALT TANKERS ARE NOT DESIGNED FOR HIGH PRESSURE EXPERIENCED WHEN 350 DEGREE OIL & WATER MIX.
column169: IMPLEMENTING NEW PROCEDURE FOR OUR DISPATCHERS/DRIVERS. IF A TANKER SITS EMPTY FOR A PERIOD OF TIME (1 WK OR MORE) AND HAS PRODUCT STRIP 1 1/2 OR WIDER ON BOTTOM THAT PREVENTS A GOOD VISUAL EXAMINATION FOR MOSITURE, THE 1ST TIME IT IS LOADED, DRIVER WILL LOAD 1/4 OF CAPACITY & WAIT 15 MIN LISTENING FOR RUMBLING/CRACKLING SOUNDS ASSOCIATED WITH WATER. IF PRODUCT REMAINS STABLE, CONTINUE LOADING.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON 05/09/2013, AT 12:04 HRS CDT, I RECEIVED A CALL REGARDING A SMELL OF POSSIBLE PROPANE IN THE INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) RAILROAD, SOUTH YARD, TRK #2. SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION OF TRACKS REVEALED THAT SOURCE OF ODOR WAS EMANATING FROM CAR GATX 95590 FROM UNDER THE VALVE BOX WHICH WAS SEALED WITH # TBS 101241 (SEE PHOTO). I REMOVED THE SEAL AND EXAMINED THE INTERIOR OF THE VALVE BOX COMPARTMENT AND NOTED THAT THE VAPOR PLUG WAS LOOSE AND SUBSEQUENTLY WRENCH TIGHTENED PLUG. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE "VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE" WAS DEFECTIVE AS A STRONG ODOR OF PRODUCT WAS DETECTED.    CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY PLACED IN ISOLATION ON OLD RIP TRACK #3 TO PREVENT ANY EXPOSURE OF VAPOR TO YARD PERSONNEL. I PLACED A CALL TO HAZMAT CONTRACTOR, "SUNPRO" WHO RESPONDED AND SUBSEQUENTLY REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE AT 1930 THIS DATE. SEAL WAS PLACED ON VALVE HOUSING BOX WITH #IHBPD 005311.    CAR IS CURRENTLY ON HOLD PENDING FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL.
column169: SHIPPER ADVISED TO CONSIDER BEST PRACTICES AND REVIEW OF CURRENT POLICIES PRIOR TO RELEASE OF CAR.

column168: DRIVER HEARD A TIRE BLOW OUT. HE STOPPED TO INVESTIGATE AND FOUND HE HAD A WHEEL FIRE. HE USED HIS EXTINGUISHER AND CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. FIRST RESPONDER HAD NO WATER, HAD TO WAIT FOR SECOND FIRE TRUCK. MATERIAL CAME OUT OF TRAILER DOOR WHEN LATCHES FAILED DUE TO FIRE. MATERIAL WAS DILUTED AND WASHED AWAY WITH FIRE CONTAINMENT. MATERIAL WAS LOST WHEN DELIVERED AND WASHED AWAY BY RAIN.
column169: IT IS SPECULATED THAT THE FIRE WAS STARTED WHEN A BEARING FAILED IN THE TRAILER HUB. THE HUB WAS A SEALED TYPE, USED TO PROLONG THE LIFE OF THE BEARING AND SEALS TO KEEP SUCH FAILURES FROM OCCURRING. NO ACTIONS COULD HABE BEEN TAKEN BY THE DRIVER TO CHANGE THE OUTCOME. FIRST RESPONDERS SHOULD HAVE BEEN BETTER PREPARED TO FIGHT THE FIRE.

column168: Tank car GATX 5851 was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area while in the railyard. GATX 5851 was cordoned off awaiting inspection by a mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder reported the leak source was at the liquid valve's threaded connection.  The responder reduced the internal pressure within GATX 5851 which stopped the commodity release at the base of the liquid valve. Afterwards, the liquid valve was tool tightened one full turn on its threaded connection to fully secure the liquid valve at its threaded connection. Spillage on GATX 5851 was neutralized along with impacted ballast under GATX 5851.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On May 21, 2013, a Vitran terminal experienced the release of UN2924 flammable liquid from a tote due to a leaking valve. It was reported that the trailer floor, asphalt and storm drain were impacted. Absorbents were applied to the impacted trailer floor and asphalt and worked in thoroughly. A vacuum truck was utilized to flush the storm drain and collect all freestanding product. All contaminated material was containerized for transportation and disposal.

On May 23, 2013, a Vitran tractor trailer experienced the release of UN3082 product due to a vehicular accident. It was reported that an area of the trailer, roadway, soil shoulder and storm drain were impacted. Absorbents were applied to the impacted asphalt and trailer floor and worked in thoroughly. The impacted soil was excavated. Absorbent boom was placed in the storm drain and at the outfall. All contaminated material was containerized for transportation and disposal. column168: CN mechanical department employee reported a "hissing" noise coming from the top tank car GATX 70618 (L / Liquefied Petroleum Gases) during a train inspection at the CN Mays Yard, Kenner, LA. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting product vapor coming the pressure relief valve. The car's pressure was checked by installing a pressure gauge on the sample line, showing approximately 145 psi. Further investigation noted the pressure relief valve's O-rings were worn and deteriorated.  O-rings changed and the leak stopped. Car released to shipper.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: CN Mechanical department employee noted product coming from the top of tank car ACFX 95302 (L / Sulphuric Acid, Spent) during an outbound inspection at the CN Harrison Yard, Memphis, Tn. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting liquid coming from the protective housing. Upon further inspection the liquid line plug was less than tool tight.  The plug required two turns to close and the leak was secured.  The exterior of the railcar was neutralized and decontaminated.  Car was released to shipper for movement to destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: THE CON-WAY DRIVER PULLED INTO THE TRUCK STOP AND DISCOVERED A STICKY MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER APPROXIMATELY 5 FEET FROM THE DOORS. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE CON-WAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT. THE CON-WAY SAFETY DEPARTMENT CALLED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (TEAM) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. THE TEAM DONNED PROPER PPE AND MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER.  AN UNSECURED 55 GALLON DRUM OF TOLUENE SOLUTION WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WAS ALSO BULGING. A CRACK APPROXIMATELY 1/2 INCH LONG IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM HAD CAUSED THE RELEASE (SEE PICTURES).
column169: We will be contacting the customer and relay our response findings for the goal of more proper securement of their cargo to prevent this from re-occurring. We also train our drivers in proper load securement of hazmat loads in further preventing these occurrances from happening.

column168: A 10,000 gallon tanker truck hauling fuel oil went off the road and rolled down an embankment.  The tanker trukc had multiple compartments.  Piping for the rear comprtment broke and approximately 1,800 gallons of fuel oil leaked.  The remaining fuel in the tanker was pumped out into a second truck.  A spill response company responded to the release and began recovering the lost product with a vacuum truck.  The lost product had flowed into a bouldery area with shallow groundwater at approximately 2 feet, so the product was found in many small pools.  The vac truck recovered product for three days.  Absorbent booms were trenched into the ground downgradient of the release area.  Absorbent pads were placed into all of the small pools and are being replaced as necessary,  Most of the product has been reovered, probably less than 100 gallosn are left to recover.
column169: The driver was expereienced and had received adequate training.  The time of the accident was early in the evening.  Due to the high embankment peerhaps a gaurd rail would have been able to keep the driver from exiting the roadway.

column168: On 5/15/2013, approximately 4:15 p.m. a seasoned veteran of Chemicals Inc., was in the process of cleaning dried Caustic material from around the discharge valve and cap assembly on our tote. Our SOP for this type of work is to strap any tote to the mast of the fork truck if you are doing anything with the tote besides loading it on a truck. This employee did not follow those instructions. To clean the discharge area of the tote properly, he needed to raise the forks approximately 3 feet. In doing so, he did not realize the tote, as it was positioned on the forks, was in a forward slant. There was already water on the forks and the base of the tote is plastic. After he stopped the fork truck and raised the forks, the material was sloshing back and forth just enough to cause the tote to slide. As the tote slid off the tip if the forks, the front, or top of the tote fell forward and down while the back of the was going to drop. When it did, all in one motion, the base of the tote hit the ground. At that point the base broke in two as two of the plastic bolts that hold the base of the tote to the bottom of the tote broke at the point of impact. This action caused the bottom of the tote itself, split open. That crack, or separation is jagged and approx 24 inches long. Fortunately, the tote was in our Wash Rack area that has collection basins and floor drains that empty into our Neutralization Tanks. From the time the tote hit the floor until the material actually stopped seeping through the crack was approximately 15 minutes. The remainder of the material that was left in the tote was pumped over into a couple of 55 gallon plastic drums. This tote was manufactured by Snyder Industries in February, 2000. Tote serial # 0002345342-
column169: The employee responsible for this action is a 42 year veteran of Chemicals Incorporated, with an impeccable safety record. I don't feel our procedures should be changed as they work well for us when followed properly. The type, size and material of construction are exactly what should be for this material. I feel that any tote would have failed under the same conditions. We will complete an internal "Corrective Action" form and place in the employee's file.

column168: Four 55 gal plastic drums of Sodium Hypochlorite 12.5% (Bleach) with vented bungs were shrink wrapped and on a pallet. The pallet was loaded in the nose of the trailer on Friday along with other pallets of freight so the load would be ready for departure on the following Monday morning. Harcros Chemicals driver, Richard Jensen, while in route to make a delivery, thought he may have a problem. He found a safe place to get off the road and called his Manager. When checking, he found that one drum of Bleach in the nose of the trailer had busted. He immediately placed the drum on its side and put absorbent in the area where the material was.
column169: The drum had built up pressure inside the trailer over the weekend and evidently the vented bung did not work properly by allowing pressure to escape the drum. The drum split on the side approximately 12 inches from the bottom of the drum. The four drums of Bleach with vented bungs should not have been loaded on the trailer and sat for three days in the heat which caused the pressure to expand in one of the drums. We re-trained the driver on our company procedure to not pre-load products that are in vented containers.

column168: Tank car UTLX 201047 was reported leaking from its top fitting area during an inbound BNSF train's mechanical inspection in the railyard. Further inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed that the leak source was at the liquid valve's mounting flange. One flange bolt stud nut was finger loose and the other three bolt stud nuts were at least 1/2 turn loose. The responder properly tool tightened all bolt stud nuts which ended any further commodity release. UTLX 201047 was isolated in the railyard awaiting cleaning of commodity spillage from the shell of UTLX 201047 which was accomplished on 6/04/2013 by contract responders.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

THE SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE DMP AND A 12 HR RESPONDER ARRIVED IMMEDIATELY, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE PKG WAS CONTAINED (NO RELEASE BEYOND INTERNAL CARTON) AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. THE INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF CORRUGATED DIVIDERS AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 350 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: Upon my arrival I observed a leak coming from the bottom outlet valve , approximately 1 small drip every 10-15 minutes.  An absorbant pad was already in place under the drip.  I inspected the bottom outlet valve area and located the leak coming from the bottom outlet valve handle, from the packing gland area.  I located the retention nut on the packing gland and tightened it, it was able to be tightened 6 whole turns and the leak stopped.  I cleaned the source of the leak and monitored it for approximately 1 hour to confirm the leak was stopped.  The leak was stopped and the car proceeded to destination.  The leak occurred for approximately 2 hours releasing less than 1 gallon is my estimate.

column168: Upon my arrival I located the PROX44029 making a hissing sound from the Manway.  I located the leak and identified that the manway had a missing gasket.  With assistance from NRC I opened the manway and placed a compatable gasket on the car with permission that the gasket I had was compatable per Inergy the shipper.  The gasket was placed on the PROX44029 and the manway was closed and secured to tool tight.  Stopping the leak and then the car was released to proceed.  The gas vapors were located and reported, from time of report to completions of repairs was approximately 4 hours leaving me with an estimate of vapors approximately 10 pounds.

column168: On May 28, 2013 at approximately 13:58 hours CSX train Q40927 was operating westbound on # 1 main track at Milepost BAK 87.4, on the Philadelphia Subdivision, when it struck a  northbound tandem axle truck loaded with a roll-off type dumpster loaded with garbage. The Q40927 consisted of 2 locomotives, 14 loads and 31 empties, 2890 tons, 2911 feet long, and was moving at approximately 49 MPH. The collision caused a train line initiated undesired emergency brake application, and subsequently derailing the head fifteen cars. As a result of the derailment a fire broke out and then an explosion resulting in a catastrophic failure of the covered hopper UNPX 128076 resulting in a release of all its contents.      ATARI SCORE:    5(5+5+0) X (5+4) = 450

column168: Tank car HOMX 104025 was reported venting from its reclosing pressure relief device (PRD) after arrival in the railyard on a BNSF inbound train. HOMX 104025 was cordoned-off in the railyard awaiting inspection by contract responders. The responders replaced both O-ring seals in the Midland reclosing pressure relief valve (PRV) which ended any further vent by 2330 hrs. CDT, 5/21/2013. Afterwards, HOMX 104025 was monitored with no further PRV vent observed. The seat O-ring appeared to have a small gouge on its outer circumference.
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: HOKX 112260 was found by Chip Heard, MHM for UPRR, during a routine inspection.  The car was found to have 3 streams on the right side of the car.  The product was found standing in the PRV valve seat and confirmed with Ph strips.  There was no active leak when found.  The pressure on the car was checked and no pressure was reading on the guage.  The car was set out and bubble tested on 5/14 by Transi-tech and no leakage was found.  The leak could have possibly been caused by over pressurization from a surge during humping activity.  The car was released back into transporation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The tank car TGAX 131347 was discovered to have a burst frangible rupture disk by Manager of Hazardous Materials Tom Robinson Jr. in Livonia LA on 5/16/2013.  Manager Robinson replaced the rupture disk, secured the cover, and remediated the top and sides of the car.  The car was released to destination after remediation was complete.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, FIVE (5) 5-GALLONS PAILS OF OPTIMUM, FLOOR FINISHER, WERE DISCOVERED DAMAGED. APPARENTLY, THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE PAILS WERE RELEASED INSIDE TRAILER, AS A RESULT OF IMPROPER LOADING. APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT RELEASED TO TRAILER FLOOR AND ASPHALT BENEATH TRAILER. SOUTH BRUNSWICK FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. THE STAPLES FACILITY WAS EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS, WHILE SOUTH BRUNSWICK FD HAZMAT PERSONNEL ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND COORDINATED RESPONSE EFFORTS. ATLANTIC RESPONSE WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ATLANTIC RESPONSE UTILIZED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT, WHICH WAS RECOVERED AND CONTAINERIZED, ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED PAILS, PENDING DISPOSAL IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO AN IMPERVIOUS SURFACE, AND DID NOT IMPACT SURFACE SOILS OR THREATHEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.
column169: STAPLES WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND REINFORCE SAFE HANDLING PROCEDURES AND DRIVER SAFETY TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: AN AMEROCHEM CORP. TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS DELIVERING IN A MOUNTAINOUS AREA OF ROUTE 9, POLK COUNTY,NC, CAME AROUND A CURVE UPON A STALLED PICK-UP TRUCK AND WAS UNABLE TO STOP COMPLETELY OR STEER CLEAR BEFORE STRIKING THE RIGHT REAR CORNER OF THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER STOPPED THE TRUCK ON THE NARROW STEEP SHOULDER BUT AFTER A FEW SECONDS THE EMBANKMENT GAVE WAY AND THE RIG ROLLED OVER 120 DEGREES DOWN A HILL.  ONE OF A NUMBER OF 330 GAL IBCs WAS CRUSHED BY ANOTHER FULL IBC AND LEAKED ITS CONTENTS FROM A 12 INCH CRACK IN THE SIDE OF THE IBC. A HAZMAT RESPONSE COMPANY (STAT, LENOIR,NC) REMOVED ALL CONTAINERS AND ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL. NO ENVIROMENTAL DAMAGE EXPECTED.

OUR TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO PARK HIS VEHICLE IN THE TRUCK PARKING AREA OF THE REST AREA. OUR DRIVER PULLED THE TRUCK BETWEEN TWO OTHER TRACTOR TRAILERS STRIKING ONE TRAILER CAUSING A 3" TEAR IN OUR TANKER. THE TEAR WAS CAUSED BY A HINGE FROM THE OTHER VEHICLE. OUR DRIVER REALIZED THE INCIDENT, NOTIFIED 911 AND THE OTHER DRIVER. OUR DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER VALVE SYSTEM TO DIVERT INTO ANOTHER COMPARTMENT THE JET FUEL FROM THE COMPROMISED COMPARTMENT. APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF JET-A FUEL WAS SPILLED TO ASPHALT AND SOIL.    THE RELEASE LASTED APPROXIMATELY 3 MINUTES BEFORE OUR DRIVER STOPPED THE LEAK. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS AT THE SITE ON STANDBY. TERPENING TRUCKING CONTACTED OP-TECH ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES TO RESPOND TO THE RELEASE. TERPENING TRUCKING ALSO RESPONDED WITH THEIR OWN SPILL EQUIPMENT TRAILER. TERPENING TRUCKING ALSO DISPATCHED ANOTHER DRIVER TO THE AREA TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT OFF OF THE DAMAGED TRAILER. ALL RESPONDERS WERE ON SITE WITHIN THE HOUR. THE JET FUEL WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE OTHER TRAILER, THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT BOOM AND SPEEDI DRY.    THAT EVENING THE AFFECTED AREA WAS ISOLATED FROM PUBLIC TRAVEL. OP-TECH ENVIROMENTAL RETURNED TO THE SITE THE NEXT DAY TO CLEAN THE AFFECTED AREA INCLUDING THE REMOVAL OF SOIL AND STONE. REPLACEMENT STONE WAS BROUGHT IN. ALL AFFECTED SOIL/STONE REPLACEMENT WAS APPROVED BY NY STATE DEC ALONG WITH THE NY STATE THRUWAY REPRESENTATIVE. THE AREA WAS TESTED FOR READINGS FOR VAPOR.
column169: REVIEW WITH OUR TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT AND DRIVERS THE ENTIRE INCIDENT, SHARE THE NEED FOR BETTER AWARENESS IN TRANSPORTING AND VEHICLE HANDLING.

PER HANDILING BY THE AIRLINE, NIPPON CARGO AIRLINES, BEFORE LOADING ONTO AN AIRLINE ULD, 1 PIECE OF 233 WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE LITHIUM METAL BATTERY LABEL ON THE SIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THIS MAIL PIECE IS IDENTIFIED WITH USPS CONTRACT NUMBER ICAIR121AS AT 3.3 KILOGRAMS WITH A DESTINATION OF TOKYO INTL JAPAN POST. PER THE DISCOVERY OF THIS LITHIUM METAL BATTERY LABEL, THE PIECE WAS SEPERATED AND HELD FOR RETURN TO THE USPS.    THIS MAIL PIECE WAS NOT MOVED ON KZ109/25MAY13, HOWEVER RETURNED TO USPS AMC SFO ON 25MAY13 13:00.  PLEASE BE ADVISED NO INCIDENT.

column168: The shipment in question was mistakenly classified as an "lATA-Biological Substance, Category B, Class 6.2, UN3373." This shipment contained twenty-five two ml vials of a cell bank of Clostridium botulinum, intended for offsite storage, and should have been shipped under the proper shipping name of "Infectious substance, affecting humans UN 2814/Class 6.2 C. botulinum. " consistent with Revance's internal approved shipping procedure and applicable DOT/IATA regulations. The shipment arrived safely and undamaged to its intended and approved recipient by cargo airplane. The incident was discovered by the recipient and Revance Therapeutics Inc. was notified on 05/23/2013. Revance immediately investigated the incident and discovered the omission was due to an oversight of the shipping employee. The employee had incorrectly concluded that the lATA-Biological Substance, Category B, Class 6.2, UN3373 classification was applicable to any shipment in a freeze dried solid state and that the shipment was finished product containing Botulinum Toxin Type A, which would have been correctly classified as an IATA biological product. Although the employee had completed all required external and internal training prior to the incident, the employee mistakenly deviated from the internal approved shipping procedure. The employee has received additional training and now clearly understands that the lATA-Biological Substance, Category B, Class 6.2, UN3373 classification is applicable only to finished biological products and that is not to be applied based on the physical state of the material being shipped.
column169: Revance's shipping request form and operating procedures are being changed to ensure that the person requesting shipments containing C. botulinum or Botulinum Toxin properly classifies all materials to be shipped with the correct proper shipping name prior to shipment. The procedures will also implicitly state categories of different materials and their respective proper shipping names. All employees shipping or requesting material to be shipped will be retrained on the new approved procedures with respect to proper classification to prevent future occurrences of this type. These procedural changes will ensure that the material will be properly classified by the person who understands its properties best before the materials are offered for shipment.

column168: On May 26, 2013, ERTS was contacted by Halliburton in regards to a Hydrochloric Acid Solution release at the referenced well site.  Per the bill of lading the solution is 15% Hydrochloric Acid.  The material was released due to a faulty seam on the CTMV.  It was originally estimated that approximately 500-800 gallons of the referenced material was released due to the incident.  ERTS dispatched A Clean Environment to the site to perform remediation activities.  A Clean Environment personnel arrived on site and met with personnel on site which performed initial response.  It was determined that approximately 3,025 gallons of material was released from the CTMV as the load originally contained 3,800 gallons and approximately 775 gallons of material was pumped from the CTMV once the leak was discovered.

column168: Dispatch number 0105 / 1pc weighing 5.1kgs, consisted of a parcel containing several containers of perfumery products (UN1266 / total net qty. 2.5L).  The mail shipment originated in New York (JFKIA) and was accepted by Emirates from the United States Post Office as a mail consignment, under document number CN38: US53AJF11644.  The parcel was then transported on flight EK204 on June 01st, 2013 from JFK International Airport to Dubai International Airport.  The shipment was packaged in a way that prevented Emirates’ handling staff from verifying its contents without opening the parcel. Contents were discovered during a routine x-ray screening of transit mail by the Dubai Police.  After Dubai Police opened the package, it was discovered that the internal containers contained perfume bottles in original packaging.  Hazmat documentation was not provided to Emirates by the shipper at the time of tender.  After classifying shipment as suspect D.G., Emirates contacted the shipper for confirmation of the contents.  At which point the shipper confirmed that the perfumes had been shipped in the US Mail in error.  The shipment is currently being held in Dubai, until shipper appoints an agent to perform proper markings, labeling, and documentation.  Only after all IATA/ICAO and FAA requirements have been met, the shipment will be moved to its final destination of Mahe, Seychelles.

Tanker was loaded at shipper.  Driver then departed and drove approx 4 miles to truck stop.  Upon inspection of tanker at truck stop the driver saw a trickle of material coming from tanker manway dome.  Spill protocol was followed and Rineco dispatch ER that was two miles from location to the scene.  LA HazMat Police were called.  Material was cleaned up and material was transfer to new tanker.

The cause of the failure was a small cut on the top of the tote.  It was unnoticeable until moved inside trailer.  Upon movement it caused the contents to move inside container and leak from the top of the tote.  No envirnomental impact.  Moved from trailer to dock until final customer disposition.

Trailer 317-7504 was being unloaded at the dock.  The driver noted a funny smell when he opened the door but started to unload the trailer.  After he removed a few pieces he noticed there was a green puddle in the middle of the trailer.  He then removed the dunnage from around the next 2 pieces of freight and saw one was a 120 gallon tote that was covered in a green liquid that appeared to be dry.  When I approached the trailer I did not notice a smell but did see the green puddle and residue on the top and sides of the tote in question.  I retrieved the Hazmat Bill from the driver and looked up the shipping name.  When I saw that it was toxic as well as corrosive I shut the trailer door and dock door as well and instructed the Supervisor not to open the door up until I called the safety department.  From what I could see on the tote the leak appeared to be coming from around the base of the lid.  So I assumed it was splashed out during transit as it was not currently leaking.  Cleaned up by ERTS.

column168: After arrival on an inbound BNSF intermodal train, intermodal container HLXU 116546 (an imported shipment from China) was lifted onto a chassis for out-gate and highway furtherance. One of the chassis' landing legs collapsed tipping HLXU 116546 onto its side atop the asphalt ground surface. Liquid commodity leaked out from the container's rear doorway. The spillage was contained by absorbent booms and granular absorbent. HLXU 116546 was up righted onto protective plastic sheeting. Lading inspection revealed two composite poly IBC's incurred punctures by their outer metal framing system which was damaged during interior load shift impacts when HLXU 116546 landed on its side. Also, other IBC's were noted with commodity seepage from their closure caps. The free commodity liquid on the asphalt was vacuumed with absorbent materials collected. Afterwards, the ground impact area was power-washed. The remaining commodity within the leaking IBC's was transferred into other suitable IBC's. After all lading in HLXU 116545 was removed, inspected for damages and decontaminated; the interior of HLXU 116545 was power-washed and cleaned. Several other non-leaking IBC's were transferred into new suitable IBC's due to outer metal frame damage and spilled commodity contamination. All lading was reloaded into another intermodal container for furtherance. All collected spilled commodity; cleaning rinsate and materials; and emptied damaged IBC's were earmarked for appropriate disposal.

column168: The shipment was discovered in the Peabody, MA FedEx station. A previous shipment of the same material was shipped in April 2013 but we did not learn of the contents until we had lost custody of the shipment. In this case there were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The SDS indicates the contents are 96% pure mised with Hydroguinone. The FAA was notified, I spoke to Hazmat Manager Kate Zamparelli. SA Sharon Witt responded to the FedEx station for the investigative portion. It is believed to be an Inhalation Hazard in addition being forbidden shipment by air. We are holding the package in a salvage drum awaiting a disposition from the FAA.

column168: THE DRIVER PULLED OVER TO CHECK HIS LOAD WHEN HE NOTICED A LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF HIS TRAILER. JUDGING BY THE LOCATION OF THE LEAK THE DRIVER IMMEDIATE RECOGNIZED THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS FROM DRUMS OF ACID IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER THEN CALLED HIS OFFICE FOR ASSISTANCE. BEAVER EXPRESS THEN CONTACTED ENVIROMENTAL MANAGEMENT WHO DISPATCHED A LOCAL SUBCONTRACTOR TO THE SITE TO CLEANUP THE RELEASED ACID AND OVERPACK THE LEAKING DRUM. HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, INC (HMRI) MOBILIZED TO THE SITE AND LOCATED THE TRAILER. CREW MEMEBERS SUITED UP AND ENTERED THE TRAILER AND LOCATED THE LEAKING DRUM. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS THEN PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE CREW NOTED THE DRUM WAS DAMAGED ON THE BOTTOM FROM A NAIL PROTRUDING UP FROM A PALLET. THE CREW BEGAN THE NEUTRALIZATION OF THE RELEASED ACID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE PRODUCT WHICH HAD RAN OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE GROUND WAS ALSO NEUTRALIZED AND SHOVELED UP AND PLACED INTO A DRUM. ALL WASTE ITEMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE.
column169: VISUALLY INSPECT PALLETS FOR SHARP EDGES PRIOR TO LOADING OR BEING PLACED INTO USE.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND PREPARED TO HOOK THE TRACTOR TO THE TRAILER WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED A GREEN LIQUID UNDER THE TRAILER. CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT FOR CLEANUP ASSISTANCE. MR. KETTMAN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORATION, LLC (ERLLC) TO RESPOND TO THE LEAKING TRAILER. THE ERLLC CREW MOBILIZED TO THE SITE AND LOCATED THE TRAILER. THE CREW PHD THE GREEN LIQUID AND CONFIRMED IT WAS A CORROSIVE MATERIAL. THE CREW REVIEWED THE BOL AND DETERMINED THE LIQUID ORIGINATED FROM A PAIL OF "ZEP HEAVY DUTY DEGREASER." THE CREW DIAPERED THE TRAILER WHICH WAS MOVED TO THE LOADING DOCK AREA. A SMALL PUDDLE OF DEGREASED REMAINED ON THE CONCRETE. NEUTRALIZING AGENTS WERE USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE DEGREASWER WHICH WAS SOLIDIFIED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A WASTE DRUM. THE CREW BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER TO FIND A PALLET IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER HAD FALLEN OVER DUE TO IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING. THE CREW SORTED THROUGH THE PAILS AND REMOVED SEVEN (7) PAILS WHICH APPEARED TO BE TOO DAMAGE FOR TRANSPORTATION. THESE 7 PAILS WERE OPENED AND POURED INTO A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM. THE CREW CONTINUED TO CLEAN THE TRAILER FLOOR AND REMAINING PAILS OF PRODUCT. NEUTRALIZER WAS USED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND REMAINING PAILS OF PRODUCT. THE CREW RESTACKED THE PALLET WITH THE REMAINING PAILS. EACH PAIL WAS INSPECTED PRIOR TO RESTACKING. ONCE THE PALLET WAS RESTACKED, THE CREW SHRINK WRAPPED THE PAILS TO THE PALLET AND SECURED THE PALLET IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  THE 55 GALLON POLY DRUM OF WASTE MATERIALS WAS LABELED AND LEFT ON THE DOCK FOR LATER DISPOSAL.
column169: Ensure proper blocking and bracing is in place before pulling away from the loading dock.

column168: ON 5/31/2013 AT 0506 HOURS I WAS DISPATCHED TO A REPORT OF AN ACCIDENT AT THE NATCHER PARKWAY AND WENDALL FORD EXPRESSWAY, I ARRIVED AND FOUND UNIT 1 OFF THE ROADWAY IN THE DITCH ON THE WEST BOUND NATCHER PARKWAY EXIT RAMP. UNIT 1, A TRACTOR TRAILER HAD GONE THROUGH THE GUARDRAIL AND DOWN AN EMBANKMENT. THE SEMI ROLLED OVER AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF TIMES, HIT SEVERAL TREES ON A WOOD LINE, AND CAME TO REST ON THE DRIVER SIDE. THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR OF DIESEL FUEL AND FIRE UNITS FOUND THAT DIESEL FUEL WAS LEAKING FROM THE TRUCK IN TO THE CORN FIELD BEHIND THE TREE LINE. FIRE UNITS WORKED ON CUTTING THE DRIVER FREE FROM THE SEMI. HE WAS REMOVED AND TRANSPORTED TO OMHS. FIRE UNITS WERE ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT THE FUEL WAS COMING FROM THE TANKS THE TRACTOR AND NOT THE TRAILER. THE TRUCK WAS HAULING A TANKER THAT HAD APPROXIMATELY 8500 GALLONS GASOLINE. NONE OF THE GASOLINE HAD BEEN REPORTED TO THIS DEPUTY TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE TANKER AFTER LEAVING THE SCENE. DAVIESS CO. EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AND STATE FIRE MARSHALL WERE ALSO ON SCENE DUE TO THE FUEL LEAK. THE DIESEL FUEL THAT ESCAPED FROM THE TRACTOR HAD RUN OFF ON TO A DITCH NEARBY. A BACK HOE WAS BROUGHT IN AND THEY CONSTRUCTED A DAM TO STOP MORE FUEL FROM GETTING IN THE DITCH. EMA AND THE FIRE MARSHALL CONTACTED A COMPANY TO COME IN AND PUMP THE FUEL OUT OF THE TANKER BEFORE MOVING IT. A LAWN CARE COMPANY WAS ALSO CALLED IN TO REMOVE THE TREES THAT WERE KNOCKED DOWN BY THE SEMI AND THAT WERE UNDER THE SEMI. MCCARTY'S TOWING CAME TO REMOVE THE TRUCK. THE STATE ROAD DEPT. ALSO ARRIVED TO PUT UP BARRELS WERE THE GUARDRAIL HAD BEEN KNOCKED OUT AND TO CLOSE THE RAMP SO THAT CREWS COULD CLEAN THE WRECK UP. THE DAMAGED PROPERTY WAS A GUARDRAIL AND STREET LIGHT. THE DIRT FROM THE FIELD WAS ALSO CONTAMINATED AND HAD TO BE REMOVED. THE FIELD ALSO HAD CROP PLANTED AND WAS DESTROYED. THE OWNER OF THE FARM IS JOE GOETZ. HE STATED THAT THE FARM DOES NOT HAVE AN ADDRESS BUT IS TO THE NORTH OF THE NATCHER WEST BOUND RAMP AND IS TO THE EAST OF THE CROSS CREEK SUBDIVISION. THE TANKER WAS EMPTIED AND REMOVED. THE ROADWAY WAS CLOSED FOR THE DAY WAS REOPENED LATER THAT EVENING. THE ROADWAY DID NOT HAVE ANY SKID MARKS. THE SEMI HIT THE GUARD RAIL IN THE CURVE AND HIT A LIGHT POLE. THERE ARE TIRE MARKS IN THE DIRT AND GOUGE MARKS IN THE GROUND AT THE BOTTOM OF THE HILL. AT THE BOTTOM OF THE HILL I LOCATED THE DIAMOND PLATE DOOR THAT GOES TO THE BOX ON THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK. THERE ARE SEVERAL MORE GOUGE MARKS ON THE GROUND BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OF THE HILL AND WHERE THE TRUCK CAME TO REST. THE TRUCK HAD ROLLED AND HIT A TREE LINE ON THE EDGE OF THE CORNFIELD KNOCKING DOWN THE TREES AND COMING TO A REST ON THE DRIVER SIDE. THE ROOF WAS CUT OFF TO REMOVE THE DRIVER. A DEPUTY WENT TO THE HOSPITAL TO SPEAK WITH THE DRIVER AND HE STATED THAT HE WAS NOT SPEEDING, NOT DRINKING, AND DID NOT FALL ASLEEP. HE STATED THAT HE WENT IN THE TURN AND HIT THE GUARD RAIL AND LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE. THE E.R. STATED THAT HE HAD CUTS TO HI

column168: While driving at 63 MPH in the rightmost lane of the Interstate, another vehicle changed into our driver's lane and our driver swerved to the left to avoid a collision. The maneuver broke the tractor's fifth wheel and the CTMV disconnected from the tractor and rolled onto its right side. The tractor did not rollover. Product began leaking from a loose CTMV washout cap. State troopers and local Fire responders arrived and placed plastic spill containment pools to contain the leaking product. We dispatched a Hazardous Material team and another CTMV and transloaded the product from the damaged CTMV. Approximately 150 gallons of product was released over a 12 hour period. Released material was contained and removed from the accident site. Our event 37134

column168: SUNDAY MAY 12, 2013 APPROXIMATELY 6:10 PM, DRIVER KEITH DAWSON HAS A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WHILE DELIVERING FUEL AT 3201 HARBOR BLVD. IN COSTA MESA, CA. THE SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF MR. DAWSON FAILING TO PROPERLY SECURE A DOWNSPOUT FITTING THE STATION'S GROUND TANK. MR. DAWSON USED THE MATERIAL IN HIS SPILL KIT BUT WAS UNABLE TO PREVENT APPROXIMATELY 2-3 GALLONS OF GASOLINE FROM ENTERING THE STORM DRAIN. EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS AND COX PETROLEUM MANAGEMENT (ANNETTE AND BRANDI HART) WERE NOTIFIED AND REPORTED TO THE SCENE. THE FOLLOWING TIMES ARE APPROXIMATE:  - 6:10 PM SPILL OCCURRED  - 6:15 PM TERMINAL MANAGER ANNETTE HARD WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION  - 6:20 PM TOM DAVIS (SAFETY SUPERVISOR) WAS NOTIFIED VIA PHONE CALL FROM ANNETTE HART.  - 6:50 PM ANNETTE HARD ARRIVED ON SCENE AND NOTICED FUEL IN THE STORM DRAIN. FIRE DEPARTMENT AND ORANGE COUNTY PUC (JAMES FORTUNA) WERE ALREADY ON SCENE AND HAD CONTROL OF THE SITUATION.  - 6:55 PM ANNETTE HART NOTIFIED TOM DAVIS THAT AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEANUP CREW WOULD BE NEEDED.
column169: DISCIPLINARY ACTION WAS TAKEN AGAINST DRIVER FOR NEGLIGENCE AND FAILURE TO FOLLOW WRITTEN DELIVERY PROCEDURES. column168: The product drums have pressure relief valves on the top of the 30-gallon drums. The pressure relief valves appear to be stuck open, allowing the product in the drums react with the atmosphere. The majority of the release is to be recovered for disposal and have the drums air monitored overnight.  One member of contractor's crew will remain on site to monitor drums. In the morning, a non-sparking bung tool will be used to release each bung cap under running water, allowing water to fill void in drum. It advised to in addition of air monitoring, to also measure the circumference of each drum every hour to ensure no bulging.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS PULLING OUT OF A PARKING LOT AND DID NOT SWING WIDE/PULL FORWARD ENOUGH FOR TRAILER TO MISS THE RIGHT SIDE DITCH.
